      "abstract": "Abstract Abstract This paper presents a substantivist construal of discourse ethics, which claims that we should see our engagement in public deliberation as expressing and elaborating a substantive commitment to basic moral ideas of solidarity, equality, and freedom. This view is different from Habermas\u2019s standard formalist defence of discourse ethics, which attempts to derive the principle of discursive moral justification from primarily non\u2010moral presuppositions of rational argumentation as such. After explicating the difference between the substantivist and the formalist construal, I defend the former by showing that it is not only intuitively compelling, but also particularly well equipped for addressing four important objections recently levelled against discourse ethics and its political applications (Rawls\u2019s concern that it lacks substantive guidelines, Gunnarsson\u2019s challenge that it has not been proven to be superior to alternative moral conceptions such as utilitarianism, Scanlon\u2019s complaint that it lacks an account of moral motivation, and Galston\u2019s and Young\u2019s worries that it could lead to political practices of cultural imposition). I conclude by pointing out some consequences of the previous discussion for the future of Critical Theory. Keywords: discourse ethicsdeliberative democracyHabermasRawlssubstanceprocedure Notes I thank Arash Abizadeh, Jeffrey Flynn, Matthias Fritsch, John Kerkhoven, and referees for IJPS for comments and suggestions on earlier drafts of this paper. Research for this paper was supported by grants from the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada and the Fonds Qu\u00e9becois de la Recherche sur la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 et la Culture. 1 See Habermas, 1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: pp. 86, 92\u20133, and 96\u20137; 1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: pp. 43\u20135. My reconstruction is slightly different from the formulation in Habermas (1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: p. 96), which goes as follows: \u2018(1) A definition of a universalization principle that functions as a rule of argumentation. (2) The identification of pragmatic presuppositions of argumentation that are inescapable and have a normative content. (3) The explicit statement of the normative content (e.g. in the form of discourse rules). (4) Proof that a relation of material implication holds between steps (3) and (1) in connection with the idea of justification of norms\u2019. Steps 2 and 3 in this formulation are put together in step 2 in my formulation. The assumption about the \u2018idea of justification of norms\u2019 which Habermas mentions as an auxiliary hypothesis in step 4 is mentioned in my reconstruction as step 3. These changes do not affect the content of Habermas\u2019s proof, and make more explicit the importance of the assumption of a certain view of the justification of norms. 2 (U) \u2018operationalizes\u2019, at the level of moral argumentation, what Habermas calls the general principle of discourse ethics (or of the discourse theory of morality) (D), according to which \u2018Only those norms can claim to be valid that meet (or could meet) with the approval of all affected in their capacity as participants in a practical discourse\u2019 (Habermas, 1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: pp. 66, 93; see also 1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: p. 41). The term \u2018operationalization\u2019 appears in Habermas (1998a \u2014\u2014. 1996. Between Facts and Norms, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. W. Rehg [Google Scholar]: p. 42; 1996 \u2014\u2014. 1996. Between Facts and Norms, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. W. Rehg [Google Scholar]: p. 109; 2003a \u2014\u2014. 2003a. \u201c\u2018Rightness versus Truth: On the Sense of Normative Validity in Moral Judgments and Norms\u2019\u201d. In Truth and Justification, Edited by: Habermas. 237\u201375. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. B. Fultner [Google Scholar]: p. 268). (U) operationalizes (D) in the domain of moral discourses, whereas a different principle of democratic legitimacy would operationalize (D) in the domain of political discourse. 3 Habermas (1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: p. 42). Habermas uses \u2018interests\u2019 in a wide sense, allowing for moral discourse to range over all kinds of reasons for action, including desires, needs, and conceptions of the good life. For an excellent discussion of Habermas\u2019s demand that norms protect \u2018common\u2019, \u2018general\u2019, or \u2018universalizable\u2019 interests, see Lafont (2004 Lafont, C. 2004. \u2018Moral Objectivity and Reasonable Agreement: Can Realism Be Reconciled with Kantian Constructivism?\u2019. Ratio Juris, 17(1): 27\u201351. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar]). For an important challenge to Habermas\u2019s stark contrast between the \u2018good\u2019 and the \u2018right\u2019, see McCarthy (1991 McCarthy, T. 1991. Ideals and Illusions, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: Ch. 7). 4 For a detailed discussion of Habermas\u2019s re\u2010elaboration of Kant\u2019s moral theory, see Gilabert (2005c \u2014\u2014. 2005c. \u2018Considerations on the Notion of \u201cMoral Validity\u201d in the Moral Theories of Kant and Habermas\u2019. Kant\u2010Studien, (forthcoming) [Google Scholar]). 5 At this stage Habermas is not yet considering practical discourses (i.e. argumentative communication assessing moral validity claims), but discourses as such (i.e. any argumentative communication assessing universal validity claims \u2013 claims viewed as meriting rational acceptance by every rational person on thebasis of shared reasons). The reference to practical discourses emerges in the third step of the argument. The normative presuppositions reconstructed in the second step are not normative in the moral sense: \u2018the equal distribution of communicative freedoms and the requirement of truthfulness in discourse have the status of argumentative duties and rights, not of moral duties and rights\u2019 (Habermas, 1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: pp. 44\u20135; see also 1993 \u2014\u2014. 1993. \u201c\u2018Remarks on Discourse Ethics\u2019\u201d. In Justification and Application, Edited by: Habermas. 19\u2013111. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Cronin [Google Scholar]: p. 31; 1996 \u2014\u2014. 1996. Between Facts and Norms, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. W. Rehg [Google Scholar]: p. 4; 2003b \u2014\u2014. 2003b. \u201c\u2018From Kant\u2019s \u201cIdeas\u201d of Pure Reason to \u201cIdealizing\u201d Presuppositions of Communicative Action: Reflections on the Detranscendentalized \u201cUse of Reason\u201d \u2019\u201d. In Truth and Justification Edited by: Habermas. 83\u2013130. [Google Scholar]: pp. 105\u20136). 6 For detailed and critically illuminating reconstructions of this argument see Finlayson (2000 Finlayson, J. G. 2000. \u2018Modernity and Morality in Habermas\u2019s Discourse Ethics\u2019. Inquiry, 43: 319\u201340. [Taylor & Francis Online], [Web of Science \u00ae] , [Google Scholar]); Gunnarsson (2000 Gunnarsson, L. 2000. Making Moral Sense: Beyond Habermas and Gauthier, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar]: Chs 8\u20139); and Rehg (1994 Rehg, W. 1994. Insight and Solidarity, Berkeley: The University of California Press. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar]: Ch. 3). 7 I rely here on Gunnarsson (2000 Gunnarsson, L. 2000. Making Moral Sense: Beyond Habermas and Gauthier, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar]). Despite using Gunnarsson\u2019s distinction between formalist and substantivist approaches, I depart from his view of the latter in two ways. First, I endorse Habermas\u2019s distinction between the ethical and the moral (i.e. between recommendations about how to live a good life and prescriptions about how we ought to treat each other). (It is due to this distinction that in his later works Habermas names his approach \u2018a discourse theory of morality\u2019 rather than \u2018discourse ethics\u2019.) My substantivism is moral, not ethical. Ideals of the good life are allowed as inputs of moral reasoning (see n. 3 above), but not as grounds for shaping and justifying its structure. Second, though I agree with Gunnarsson\u2019s general claim that a substantivist approach to moral thinking is desirable, I develop a substantivist account of discourse ethics itself. This is something that Gunnarsson himself does not do, though there is nothing in his text entailing that it could not or should not be done. 8 I assume here a minimal definition of solidarity as people\u2019s willingness to \u2018give each other\u2019s interests some non\u2010instrumental weight in their practical reasoning\u2019 (Mason, 2000 Mason, A. 2000. Community, Solidarity and Belonging, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar]: p. 27). 9 The formal structure of the arguments can be presented in the following way. Take \u2018p\u2019 to mean \u2018I endorse the discursive procedure of universalization\u2019; \u2018q\u2019 to mean \u2018I endorse the substantive ideas\u2019; and \u2018\u00ac\u2019 \u2018&\u2019, and \u2018\u2192\u2019 to mean, respectively, the logical operators of negation, conjunction, and the conditional. Now, the Normative Point Argument would yield \u2018\u00acq \u2192 \u00acp\u2019, from which \u2018p \u2192 q\u2019 follows. The Outrage Argument, on the other hand, would yield \u2018\u00ac (\u00acp & q)\u2019, from which \u2018q \u2192 p\u2019 follows. From the conjunction of the conclusions of the two arguments it follows, in turn, \u2018p \u2194 q\u2019, i.e. the general claim that the discursive procedure of universalization and the substantive ideas involve each other. This is not a knock\u2010out transcendental argument, but a reconstructive or maieutic one appealing to our deepest moral convictions. The productivity of this approach will become evident in section III when we consider its help in defending discourse ethics against some recent criticisms. 10 For an attempt to provide an external justification of a discursive principle of justification, see Larmore (1999 Larmore, C. 1999. \u2018The Moral Basis of Political Liberalism\u2019. Journal of Philosophy, 96(12): 599\u2013625. [Crossref], [