      "abstract": "Previous articleNext article FreeSymposium on Contestation and International RelationsIntroductionJonathan HavercroftJonathan HavercroftUniversity of Southampton Search for more articles by this author University of SouthamptonPDFPDF PLUSFull Text Add to favoritesDownload CitationTrack CitationsPermissionsReprints Share onFacebookTwitterLinked InRedditEmailQR Code SectionsMoreAntje Wiener's A Theory of Contestation makes an important intervention into the field of international norms. Norms have formed a central part of the social constructivist research agenda in international relations and international law since the pioneering works of Kratochwil and Onuf in the early 1990s.1 Social constructivism initially developed as a new theoretical approach to the study of international politics. While more traditional approaches to studying international relations, such as liberalism and realism, focused on the role that material forces, such as natural resources, economic power, and military capabilities, played in the behavior of international actors, social constructivists argued that beliefs, identities, and other non-material forces determined the behavior of international actors. Norms play a key role in social constructivist theory, specifying the expected behavior and the rights and obligations of states in the international system. Early research on norms demonstrated that social expectations of appropriate conduct (the \"logic of appropriateness\") could shape state behavior in ways that cut against a state's material interest (the \"logic of consequentialism\").2 Much of the academic debate about norms has focused on demonstrating that international norms exist and, determining under what conditions states comply with or violate them.As Wiener notes in the introduction to A Theory of Contestation, this focus leaves two key unresolved problems. First, conventional constructivist accounts of norms rely upon the social expectations of the international community to do most of the heavy theoretical lifting. But if the international community creates norms that guide state behavior, then, Wiener observes, \"the norm-generative practice of international relations \u2026 [is] almost impossible\": it relies on a community ontology, yet states with different cultures cannot share such a community because of their different national roots.3 Instead of locating norm generation in a shared community, Wiener argues that participants in the international system produce norms through contestations over appropriate behavior across the different cultures of the system.Second, much conventional constructivist research since 2000 has focused on the issue of norm compliance, or when and how states abide by or disobey norms. One way of interpreting some instances of norm non-compliance is as an act of protest or contestation by a state dissatisfied with the norm. The term \"contested compliance\" has proliferated in the academic literature since it was introduced by Michael Byers and further developed by Jutta Brunn\u00e9e and Stephen J. Toope.4 Yet this proliferation has come at the expense of conceptual precision, with scholars now using \"contested compliance\" to refer to such diverse phenomena as refusal to comply with European Union regulations, deliberative democratic practices in international organizations, and bargaining tactics deployed by states in international trade negotiations.Wiener's theory of contestation offers both an explanatory theory of how norms are contested and a normative defense of why they should be contested. Wiener's argument is threefold. First, she argues that contestation generates international norms. Second, she argues that all norms are potentially contestable. Third, she argues that because contestation is central to the generation, transformation, and implementation of norms, international relations scholars should draw upon the \"thinking tools\" developed by political theorists who work on norm contestation in the area of democratic theory.In order to develop her theory of contestation, Wiener draws upon the public philosophy of James Tully.5 Tully's work on democratic constitutionalism and agonistic political philosophy emphasizes that conflict is a form of justice. Other influential approaches to justice, such as J\u00fcrgen Habermas's work on deliberative democracy6 and John Rawls's work on political liberalism,7 see conflicts in pluralistic societies as problems to be solved through the development of procedures and norms that can achieve consensus among all participants. Tully is skeptical that finding such universally acceptable norms is possible or desirable. Instead, the justness of a society should be determined by its capacity to make space for the contestation and revision of all norms and procedures by those that they affect; the just society never seeks out a final comprehensive solution. Wiener brings Tully's political philosophy of contestation into international relations debates over norm compliance to argue that disputes over and resistance to the implementation of norms is not a problem that scholars, lawyers, and practitioners need to solve. Rather, the fact that norms can be contested is the very mark of their legitimacy.Wiener takes this central insight from Tully's work to criticize both liberal and critical varieties of constructivism. Liberal constructivists share the core social constructivist insight that international norms and institutions are socially constructed, and then go on to develop liberal conclusions from this, such as a rejection of realist power politics, evidence of how international norms foster greater cooperation between states, and a shared commitment with liberalism to a rational actor model of politics (also known as homo economicus). Against the liberal constructivists (whom she calls conventional constructivists),8 Wiener argues that Tully's insight\u2014that one can demonstrate understanding a norm by going against it\u2014can help to explain how contestation can generate norms. Tully developed this insight from a close reading of section 201 of Ludwig Wittgenstein's Philosophical Investigations, where Wittgenstein says, \"there is a way of grasping a rule which is not an interpretation, but which, from case to case of application, is exhibited in what we call 'following the rule' and 'going against it'.\"9 Wittgenstein is concerned with the questions \"what is a rule?\" and \"how do I know if someone (either myself or another) is following a rule?\" Wittgenstein's answer is that one demonstrates that one understands a rule when one can follow it (such as continuously adding 2 to a sequence of numbers\u2014e.g., 1400, 1402, 1404, etc.) by continuing to act in a manner that obeys the rule. Yet at the end of section 201 of the Philosophical Investigations, Wittgenstein left the cryptic comment that one could also demonstrate mastery of a rule by going against it.10Tully considers the remark in relation to rule following in politics. Just as a pupil demonstrates his understanding of a rule by being able to go on applying it independently, citizens in a democracy demonstrate their understanding of both the written rules (e.g., the positive law) of a society and the unwritten social norms upon which the society rests (e.g., norms about race, class, and gender roles). Part of being a citizen of a society is learning to master these rules. Tully's insight, however, is that some forms of political dissent can be examples of demonstrating that one understands the laws of a society by going against those rules. For example, acts of civil disobedience\u2014such as Rosa Parks's protest against the written segregation laws as well as the unwritten social codes that supported segregation\u2014would be examples of demonstrating that one understands a rule by explicitly going against it. As a black woman living in Montgomery, Alabama in the 1950s, she knew the rules of segregation intimately. By going against the rules, she demonstrated her understanding of them.Tully uses this insight to argue that going against the rules in society is an important feature of democratic citizenship. Part of the significance of civil disobedience is that activists are aware that they are breaking a law, but they go against the law in order to demonstrate that the law itself is unjust. Wiener takes this insight from Tully and applies it to international relations. In International Relations scholarship, especially liberal constructivism, the default assumption is that non-compliance with an international norm is a problem. Just as breaking a domestic law disrupts political order, breaking international norms disrupts international order.Wiener, following Tully and Wittgenstein, argues that not every instance of norm transgression is a case of a state either not understanding a norm or breaking it to simply advance self-interest. In some instances, states can engage in transnational disobedience (i.e., the international equivalent of civil disobedience) in order to demonstrate their dissatisfaction with a norm. Against the critical constructivists, who draw upon Habermas's distinction between arguing and bargaining to make the case that contestation about norms is appropriate only at the implementation stage,11 Wiener argues that norms can be contested at any stage in their constitution, reference, or implementation.In order to develop this theory of contestation, Wiener proposes three thinking tools: the normativity premise, the diversity premise, and cultural cosmopolitanism. The normativity premise states that scholars and practitioners must place normative considerations\u2014for example, whether or not a norm is just\u2014at the center of discussions about norm generation. The normativity premise underscores a central tension in the norms literature between sociological approaches that emphasize the ways in which norms condition behavior and legal and philosophical approaches that are concerned with the validity or justness of norms. One common critique of conventional constructivists is that in their attempt to develop explanatory theories of norms, they have bracketed out questions of whether or not norms are good or bad, just or unjust. This exclusion of the normative means that conventional constructivists often assume that the norms they study are good, thereby potentially ignoring the dark sides of some norms, and they may entirely ignore some norms that are bad (such as those that say a state should protect the interests of private capital over the interests of its least well off citizens). The normativity premise opens the door for a substantial engagement between empirical scholars of norms and scholars of international ethics to both criticize existing norms and find sounder normative foundations for international laws.The diversity premise draws upon Tully's critique of Kant and contemporary Kantian political philosophy, and states that norms must be generated through procedures that ensure cultural diversity in order to be valid. According to Tully, one of the problems of Kantian approaches to normative theorizing is that the search for categorical imperatives and universally valid principles can be culturally hegemonic. As such, Tully argues against seeking \"end states\" in normative deliberations, and instead argues that valid norms are those that are worked out through cross-cultural negotiation and premised on mutual recognition, mutual consent, and openness to future revision and contestation. Wiener's emphasis on agonistic procedures ensures that diversity is built into the process of norm generation and legitimation.Finally, the principle of cultural cosmopolitanism states that global politics is constituted through cultural practices. Drawing upon Tully once again, Wiener argues that there is an important interaction between practices of contestation and the principle of contestedness. Central to Wiener's argument is that a norm must be generated through practices open to contestation, and must continue to be open to contestation during referral and implementation, in order to secure its legitimacy. The principle of contestedness states that a norm's validity hinges on it being generated via practices of contestation. Norms that are generated univocally, without making space for challenges from actors who could be affected by that norm, are invalid.Following an introductory article by Antje Wiener that provides a concise summary of her theory,12 this symposium includes five contributions that respond to Wiener's work in a number of important and provocative ways. Christian Bueger, writing from the practice theory approach, observes that the constructivist focus on norms cannot answer questions about how and where norms originate. While Wiener accepts and incorporates these critiques of norm scholarship in her own research, A Theory of Contestation still isolates norms as an object of study. Bueger argues that, from the perspective of practice theory, Wiener's approach runs the risk of ignoring the larger structures of meaning that give norms their significance. This is because in social reality there is usually more than one norm at play in any given context, and debates about norms are just as likely to be over questions of which of a number of conflicting norms applies in a given case as they are to be over whether or not an individual norm is valid. The practice theory approach studies \"broader, collectively shared patterns of meaning and how they relate to situations of action\"13 by expanding the focus from norms to include other social phenomena, such as rules of thumb and embodied performances. Drawing upon his own research on Somali piracy, Bueger argues that Wiener's theory would be better suited as a method for studying practices of contestation than as a general explanatory or normative theory.Brent Steele responds to Wiener from a post-structuralist perspective. While he shares Wiener's desire to focus on norms and their contestation, he is concerned that A Theory of Contestation does not analyze how norms can be criticized on the basis of whom the norm governs. Steele considers two instances in which norms are not only contested but completely rejected: the American public's recent rejection of global anti-torture norms, and the rejection of liberal human rights norms originating in Europe and North America by states such as Turkey, Japan, and Russia on the grounds that these norms produce globally stratified social structures. His point is that a focus on contestation may neglect ways in which norms are avoided or abolished altogether.14In the next contribution, Sasikumar Sundaram criticizes A Theory of Contestation for not having a fully developed account of practical reason. He argues that contestation is always done through a process of giving and asking for reasons. According to Sundaram, without an account of this process of practical reasoning, Wiener's work cannot explain how specific actors justify their support for particular norms. He argues that Wiener's focus on \"multilogues\" (conversations involving more than two partners) should be supplemented by such an account.15Lisbeth Zimmerman argues that Wiener's work implicitly adopts Habermas's democratic theory when discussing international conditions of diversity. This is a provocative reading of A Theory of Contestation, since Wiener explicitly distances herself from Habermas and Habermasian inspired accounts of international relations theory in her work. Nevertheless, by situating Wiener's account of contestation within Habermasian democratic theory, Zimmerman argues that Wiener's work can help answer important questions, such as what makes a norm legitimate. Habermas argues that under domestic political conditions, norms are legitimated via institutionalized procedures that ensure that all those who could potentially be affected by a norm can have their concerns heard and taken into account. Wiener adopts this principle of norm legitimation for international politics, but expands it. Norms are legitimate only if two conditions are met. First, the Habermasian condition that a norm is valid only if all the participants in a discourse can agree on the norm. Second, a norm's validity also rests on all participants in a discourse resolving the culturally diverse implications of a norm, since the norm impacts different cultures differently. Each culture must assent that the norm respects their unique cultural traditions and practices.16Finally, Raymond Duvall and Jonathan Havercroft's piece sees Wiener, in her focus on contestation as constitutive of international norms, as developing an important and new variety of constructivist research. We suggest that she label this approach agonistic constructivism in order to draw out its affinities with agonistic approaches in democratic theory. At the same time, we question the implications of Wiener's explicitly bifocal approach to the study of norms, which examines norms from both an explanatory and a normative perspective. One of her claims is that by adopting this bifocal approach, the theory of contestation will be of value to both academic theorists and international legal practitioners. However, Duvall and I argue that there are fundamental tensions involved in speaking to these two audiences simultaneously, and press Wiener to reconsider the implications of fusing normative and empirical work on norms.17Wiener concludes the symposium with a reply to her critics that considers three main themes. First, she argues that there is a conceptual distinction in her work between regulatory and customary practices of constitutionalism with which some of her critics take issue. Regulatory practices refer to the explicit (normally written in international treaties) rules and norms of international relations. Customary practices are the implicit (normally unwritten) norms that function as a \"hidden\" global constitution. Wiener's work is aimed at bringing global customary practices to the forefront of both scholarship and activism, so that inter-cultural disputes can be discussed and resolved as part of the norm generation process. Second, Wiener argues that by using an approach that simultaneously explores the normative and empirical dimensions of norms, moments of norm contestation become opportunities through which actors can generate civic freedom within a global society. Third, Wiener responds to the suggestion from Duvall and Havercroft that A Theory of Contestation be framed as a form of agonistic constructivism by situating her work and other scholarship on contestation in the context of calls for justice grounded in practices of recognition.18A Theory of Contestation and the responses to it in this symposium open up an interdisciplinary dialogue among scholars in the political science subfields of international relations, international law, and political theory. By shifting the terrain of international norms research from questions about norm existence and compliance to how actors contest norms in their daily struggles for justice, Antje Wiener's work creates an exciting opportunity for scholars to cross boundaries between fields and between empirical and normative research. While there are significant differences among the contributors to this symposium, one thing they all agree upon is that A Theory of Contestation should find a broad audience and inspire scholars to place the study of practices of contestation at the heart of their research. Notes Jonathan Havercroft is Associate Professor of International Political Theory at the University of Southampton. His research focuses on global norms concerning state sovereignty. He is the author of Captives of Sovereignty (2011). He has recently published articles in Political Theory, Review of International Studies, Global Constitutionalism, and Constellations. He can be reached at j.haver[email protected].1. Nicholas Greenwood Onuf, World of Our Making: Rules and Rule in Social Theory and International Relations (London: Routledge, 2012); Friedrich V. Kratochwil, Rules, Norms, and Decisions: On the Conditions of Practical and Legal Reasoning in International Relations and Domestic Affairs (Cambridge, U.K.: Cambridge University Press, 1991).2. James G. March and Johan P. Olsen, \"The Institutional Dynamics of International Political Orders,\" International Organization 52 (September 1998): 943\u201369.3. Ibid.4. Michael Byers, \"The Shifting Foundations of International Law: A Decade of Forceful Measures against Iraq,\" European Journal of International Law 13 (February 1, 2002): 21\u201341; Jutta Brunn\u00e9e and Stephen J. Toope, Legitimacy and Legality in International Law: An Interactional Account (New York: Cambridge University Press, 2010).5. James Tully, Public Philosophy in a New Key: Volume 1, Democracy and Civic Freedom, 1st ed. (Cambridge, U.K.: Cambridge University Press, 2009); James Tully, Public Philosophy in a New Key: Volume 2, Imperialism and Civic Freedom, 1st ed. (Cambridge, U.K.: Cambridge University Press, 2009).6. J\u00fcrgen Habermas, \"Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Paradigm of Philosophical Justification,\" in Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, trans. Shierry Weber Nicholsen and Christian Lenhardt (Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press, 1990).7. John Rawls, Political Liberalism (New York: Columbia University Press, 1993).8. Martha Finnemore and Kathryn Sikkink, \"International Norm Dynamics and Political Change,\" International Organization 52 (September 1998): 887\u2013917.9. Ludwig Wittgenstein, Philosophical Investigations, trans. G.E.M. Anscombe, P.M.S. Hacker, and Joachim Schulte (Oxford, U.K.: Wiley-Blackwell, 2009), section 201.10. Tully, Public Philosophy in a New Key, vol. I, 65\u201367 (see note 5 above).11. Thomas Risse, \"'Let's Argue!': Communicative Action in World Politics,\" International Organization 54 (January 2000): 1\u201339.12. Antje Wiener, \"A Theory of Contestation\u2014A Concise Summary of Its Argument and Concepts,\" Polity 49 (January 2017): 109\u201325.13. Christian Bueger, \"Practices, Norms, and the Theory of Contestation,\" Polity 49 (2017): 126\u201331, at 127.14. Brent Steele, \"Broadening the Contestation of Norms in International Relations,\" Polity 49 (2017): 132\u201338.15. Sasikumar S. Sundaram, \"Norm Contestation and Global Governance: Taking Actor Configurations and Practical Reasoning Seriously,\" Polity 49 (2017): 139\u201348.16. Lisbeth Zimmermann, \"'Inter-National' Habermas: Contestation and Understanding under Conditions of Diversity,\" Polity 49 (2017): 149\u201353.17. Jonathan Havercroft and Raymond Duvall, \"Challenges of an Agonistic Constructivism for International Relations,\" Polity 49 (2017): 156\u201364.18. Antje Wiener, \"A Reply to My Critics,\" Polity 49 (2017): 165\u201384. Previous articleNext article DetailsFiguresReferencesCited by Polity Volume 49, Number 1January 2017Perpetual Struggle The Journal of the Northeastern Political Science Association Article DOIhttps://doi.org/10.1086/689979HistoryPublished online December 21, 2016 \u00a9 2017 Northeastern Political Science Association. All rights reserved.PDF download Crossref reports the following articles citing this article:Roger Karapin Perpetual Struggle, Polity 49, no.11 (Dec 2016): 1\u20134.https://doi.org/10.1086/689973Antje Wiener A Reply to My Critics, Polity 49, no.11 (Jan 2017): 165\u2013184.https://doi.org/10.1086/690101",
